  <p class="answer-text">Malpresentation &mdash; any presentation other than vertex (cephalic with occiput as denominator) &mdash; complicates approximately 4&ndash;5% of deliveries at term and is a leading indication for caesarean section in India. Breech presentation is the most common type, occurring in 3&ndash;4% of term pregnancies, and carries significant risks including cord prolapse, head entrapment, and birth asphyxia. The nurse midwife must be competent in antenatal detection, understanding of management options including external cephalic version (ECV), and safe intrapartum care.</p>
