    answer: `
<div class="in-short"><strong>In Short:</strong> Episiotomy = planned surgical incision of perineum during delivery. Types: mediolateral (most common, safer) and median. NOT routine &mdash; only when indicated. Repair with absorbable sutures.</div>

<div class="answer-section animate-slide-up">
  <h3 class="answer-section-title">Introduction</h3>
  <p class="answer-text">Episiotomy&mdash;a deliberate surgical incision of the perineum to enlarge the vaginal outlet at delivery&mdash;was once performed routinely in India but is now recommended only on a <strong>selective basis</strong> by WHO (2018) and the Indian Council of Medical Research (ICMR), as routine use has been shown to increase the risk of third- and fourth-degree tears. The nurse midwife must understand the current evidence-based indications, the correct technique for mediolateral incision, meticulous three-layer repair, and comprehensive postoperative perineal care to promote healing and prevent infection.</p>
</div>

<div class="answer-section animate-slide-up stagger-1">
  <h3 class="answer-section-title teal-title">Definition</h3>
  <div class="definition-box animate-scale-in">
    <strong>Episiotomy:</strong> A <strong>deliberate, planned surgical incision</strong> of the perineum and posterior vaginal wall made during the second stage of labour at crowning to enlarge the vaginal outlet and facilitate delivery; performed under local anaesthesia (1% lignocaine) and repaired in three layers using absorbable sutures; types include <strong>mediolateral</strong> (45&deg; from midline, most common in India) and <strong>median/midline</strong>.
  </div>
</div>


<div class="answer-section animate-slide-up">
  <h3 class="answer-section-title accent-title">Types</h3>
  <div class="answer-table-wrap"><table class="answer-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Direction</th><th>Advantage</th><th>Disadvantage</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Mediolateral</strong></td><td>45&deg; from midline</td><td>Less extension risk; most used</td><td>More painful</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Median</strong></td><td>Straight to anus</td><td>Less pain; heals better</td><td>Higher extension to 3rd/4th degree</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></div>
</div>
<div class="answer-section animate-slide-up">
  <h3 class="answer-section-title accent-title">Indications & Care</h3>
  <ul class="answer-points">
    <li>Rigid perineum; instrumental delivery; macrosomia; breech; fetal distress</li>
    <li>Given at crowning; local anaesthetic first (1% lignocaine)</li>
    <li>Repair: 3 layers (mucosa &rarr; muscle &rarr; skin) with <strong>absorbable sutures</strong></li>
    <li>Post-care: ice packs, sitz baths, perineal hygiene, analgesics, pelvic floor exercises</li>
  </ul>
</div>
<div class="remember-box"><div class="remember-title">Quick Revision</div><ul>
  <li>Episiotomy = planned surgical incision of perineum during delivery</li>
  <li>Types: mediolateral (most common, safer) and median</li>
  <li>NOT routine &mdash; only when indicated</li>
  <li>Repair with absorbable sutures.</li>
</ul></div>

<div class="flowchart animate-fade-in">
  <div class="flowchart-title">Clinical Pathway: Episiotomy</div>
  <div class="flowchart-container">
    <div class="flow-box highlight">Identification / Assessment</div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">&darr;</div>
    <div class="flow-box">History + Examination + Investigations</div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">&darr;</div>
    <div class="flow-box">Diagnosis Confirmed</div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">&darr;</div>
    <div class="flow-box">Medical Management + Nursing Care</div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">&darr;</div>
    <div class="flow-box">Monitoring + Follow-up</div>
    <div class="flow-arrow">&darr;</div>
    <div class="flow-box highlight">Evaluation of Outcomes</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="dont-confuse">
  <strong>Don't Confuse:</strong><br>
  <strong>Episiotomy vs Perineal Tear:</strong> Episiotomy is a PLANNED surgical cut to enlarge the vaginal opening during delivery. Perineal tear is UNPLANNED tissue damage that occurs spontaneously. Episiotomy is no longer done routinely &mdash; only when indicated.
</div>

<div class="answer-section animate-slide-up">
  <h3 class="answer-section-title teal-title">Conclusion</h3>
  <div class="conclusion-box">
    Episiotomy is an important topic in obstetric nursing. A thorough understanding of the clinical features, management, and complications helps the nurse provide evidence-based care and improve maternal and neonatal outcomes.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="glossary">
  <div class="glossary-title">Full Forms &amp; Easy Meanings</div>

<div class="self-test">
  <div class="self-test-title">Test Yourself (cover the answers first!)</div>

<div class="keyword-box"><strong>Keywords:</strong> <span class="kw">Episiotomy</span><span class="kw">Mediolateral</span><span class="kw">Median</span><span class="kw">Perineal care</span><span class="kw">Absorbable sutures</span></div>
</div>
</div>
`
